[[File:Herber und Baier.jpg|thumb|Herber and Baier]]
'''Maxi Herber''' (8 October 1920 – 20 October 2006) was a [[Germany|German]] [[figure skating|figure skater]] who competed in [[pair skating]] and [[single skating]]. She is the [[List of Olympic medalists in figure skating by age#Youngest champions|youngest]] figure skating Olympic champion (at the age of 15 years and 128 days) when she [[Figure skating at the 1936 Winter Olympics – Pairs|won gold in pair skating]] together with [[Ernst Baier]] at the [[1936 Winter Olympics]]. The duo revolutionized [[pair skating]], becoming the first team to perform [[figure skating jump|jumps]] side by side.{{Citation needed|date=January 2008}}

Born in [[Munich]], Herber was also an accomplished single skater, winning the German nationals three times, from 1933 to 1935. She skated for the Münchner EV (Munich EV) club.

Herber and Baier married after their skating career ended in 1940. They had 3 children. After [[World War II]] they skated in ice shows. Later the couple owned a business. In 1964 they were divorced. As a result of the divorce, she had to depend on social services to survive.{{Citation needed|date=January 2008}} Supported by the "Deutsche Sporthilfe" (German Sport help organisation) she moved to [[Oberau]] near [[Garmisch-Partenkirchen]] in [[Bavaria]]. Some years later Herber and Baier remarried, but were divorced again.

Herber suffered from [[Parkinson's disease]]. In 2000, she moved to the Lenzheim retirement home in Garmisch-Partenkirchen. Soon afterwards she had an exhibition of her [[Watercolor painting|watercolor]] paintings there. She died at age 86 in [[Garmisch-Partenkirchen]]; Herber had been Germany's oldest living female Olympic champion.{{Citation needed|date=January 2008}}

