{{Spanish name|Luciano|Divis}} {{Infobox person | name = Tania | image = Tania3.jpg | alt = <!-- descriptive text for use by the blind and visually impaired's speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software --> | caption = | birth_name = Ana Luciano Divis | birth_date = {{Birth date|1893|10|13|df=yes}} | birth_place = [[Toledo, Spain]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|1999|02|17|1893|10|13|df=yes}} | death_place = [[Buenos Aires]], Argentina | nationality = Spanish | other_names = | occupation = Tango singer | years_active = 1917-1988 | known_for = tango interpretation | notable_works = }}
'''Tania''' (13 October 1893 — 17 February 1999) was the stage name of Spanish tango singer '''Ana Luciano Divis'''. She was one of the most significant tango interpreters of her era. She was honored as an Illustrious Citizen of the City of Buenos Aires and a Personality of Argentine Culture, as well as receiving the [[Order of Isabella the Catholic]] from [[Juan Carlos I of Spain]].
==Biography== Ana Luciano Divis was born in [[Toledo, Spain]] on 13 October, but the year varies in reports from 1893<ref name="Cine Nacional">{{cite web|title=Tania|url=http://www.cinenacional.com/persona/tania|publisher=Cine Nacional|accessdate=7 January 2016|location=Buenos Aires, Argentina|language=Spanish}}</ref> to 1901,<ref name="Independent, obit">{{cite news|last1=Graham-Yooll|first1=Andrew|title=Obituary: Tania|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/obituary-tania-1080928.html|accessdate=7 January 2016|publisher=The Independent|date=15 March 1999|location=London, England}}</ref> as the artist took measures to obscure the date,<ref name="La Nacion, tribute">{{cite news|title=Tania, una diva del tango|url=http://www.lanacion.com.ar/680205-tania-una-diva-del-tango|accessdate=7 January 2016|publisher=La Nacion|date=16 February 2005|location=Buenos Aires, Argentina|language=Spanish}}</ref> though she admitted to being over 100 years old, indicating that the earlier time frame is probably more accurate.<ref name="Nacion obit">{{cite news|title=Por Tania, el tango quedó sin palabras|url=http://www.lanacion.com.ar/128493-por-tania-el-tango-quedo-sin-palabras|accessdate=7 January 2016|publisher=La Nacion|date=19 February 1999|location=Buenos Aires, Argentina|language=Spanish}}</ref> Her father, a career military officer, was Amalio Luciano and her mother was Carmen Divis. Ana was the youngest of four siblings. The family moved to Valencia when she was two and she performed in theater and singing groups as a child.{{sfn|Gutiérrez Miglio|1992|p=217}} Her older sister Isabel was a light opera performer, and to avoid confusion with her when she decided to become a performer, Ana chose to use the stage name of Tania, after a Russian school friend, because she liked the name.<ref name="La Nacion, tribute" /><ref name="Todo Tango">{{cite web|last1=Rodríguez Villar|first1=Antonio|title=Tania "His life was a movie..."|url=http://www.todotango.com/english/history/chronicle/26/Tania-%C2%ABHis-life-was-a-movie%C2%BB/|publisher=Todo Tango|accessdate=7 January 2016|location=Buenos Aires, Argentina|language=Spanish}}</ref> At the age of eighteen she formed her own company and performed a variety show<ref name="La Nacion, tribute" /> which toured [[Alicante]], [[Barcelona]], and [[Madrid]].<ref name="Pagina 12 obit">{{cite news|title=Tania se fue, buscando encontrar a Discépolo|url=http://www.pagina12.com.ar/1999/99-02/99-02-19/pag22.htm|accessdate=7 January 2016|publisher=Pagina 12|date=19 February 1999|location=Buenos Aires, Argentina|language=Spanish}}</ref> During a tour in Morocco,<ref name="El Portal del Tango">{{cite web|last1=Espinosa Bethlehem|first1=Ricardo|title=Tania|url=http://www.elportaldeltango.com/especial/Tania.htm|publisher=El Portal del Tango|accessdate=7 January 2016}}</ref> she met and married the Mexican dancer, Antonio Fernández Rodríguez,<ref name="Clarín obit">{{cite news|last1=Amuchastegu|first1=Irene|title=Murió Tania, leyenda del tango|url=http://edant.clarin.com/diario/1999/02/19/e-04201d.htm|accessdate=7 January 2016|publisher=Clarín|date=19 February 1999|location=Buenos Aires, Argentina|language=Spanish}}</ref> and became known as Mexican Tania.<ref name="their meeting">{{cite news|title=Enrique Santos Discépolo y Tania|url=http://www.lanacion.com.ar/475042-enrique-santos-discepolo-y-tania|accessdate=7 January 2016|publisher=La Nacion|date=23 February 2003|location=Buenos Aires, Argentina|language=Spanish}}</ref> Tania's only child, Anita, who later performed as Choly Mur, was born from the marriage.<ref name="La Nacion, tribute" /><ref name="El Portal del Tango" />
In 1923, they traveled to Argentina<ref name="Clarín obit" /> as part of the Iberian Troupe led by Teresita España.<ref name="El Portal del Tango" /> The initial tour included performances in Brazil, where a guitarist, Mario Pardo,<ref name="Pagina 12 obit" /> suggested she perform a tango, "Fumando espero",<ref name="La Nacion, tribute" /> which was well received and she added it to her repertoire.<ref name="Pagina 12 obit" /> Later she added the tango "Esta noche me emborracho", which would lead to her introduction to the composer who would become her life companion.<ref name="La Nacion, tribute" /> By 1926, the troupe fell apart, her marriage had floundered and her husband returned to Spain, but Tania returned to Buenos Aires, as a solo act called "The Galician of Toledo".<ref name="El Portal del Tango" /> In 1927, [[José Razzano]] introduced her to [[Enrique Santos Discépolo]]<ref name="Clarín obit" /> at a cabaret performance of the Buenos Aires version of the [[Folies Bergère]].<ref name="Independent, obit" /> Razzano wanted Discépolo to hear Tania's rendition of his song. Almost from their meeting, they were never separated, though they did not marry.<ref name="La Nacion, tribute" /> She was called Discépolo's muse,<ref name="Nacion obit" /> but both of their careers took off once they joined their artistic and personal lives. He became a noted composer of tangos and she was one of the most popular interpreters of the genre.<ref name="Independent, obit" />
[[File:Tania4.jpg|thumb|Tania and Enrique Santos Discépolo]]In the 1930s, Tania performed in live theater with shows under Discépolo's direction, including "La Perichona" and "Mis canciones" in 1932, "Wunder Bar" in 1933 and "Winter Garden" in 1935.<ref name="Pagina 12 obit" /> She sang on the radio beginning with a performance on Radio Prieto and then in 1937 sang on Radio Municipal.<ref name="El Portal del Tango" /> She worked on three films, ''[[El pobre Pérez]]'' (1937) with [[Luis César Amadori]], ''[[Four Hearts (1939 film)|Cuatro corazones]]'' (1939) and ''[[Caprichosa y millonaria]]'' (1940) both under the direction of Discépolo.<ref name="Pagina 12 obit" /> They also had successes in the 1940s, with Tania performing as a soloist on Del Pueblo, Paris and Belgrano radio stations. She performed in "El Mundo" (the World) in 1945 with Mariano Mores.<ref name="Pagina 12 obit" /> In 1946, they did a tour through Bolivia, Chile, Cuba, Mexico and Peru and then in 1947, Tania did a series on Radio Belgrano called "Cómo nacieron mis canciones" (How my songs were born) with Discépolo and made recordings with [[Columbia Records]], [[Odeon Records]] and [[RCA Victor]].<ref name="El Portal del Tango" /> She returned to live theater with "Blum"<ref name="Nacion obit" /> in 1949 and then did the same show in a final theatrical season from 1950-1951, the year Discépolo died, at the Teatro Gran Splendid.<ref name="Pagina 12 obit" />
After Discépolo's death, Tania left Argentina, making an extended tour of Latin America and Europe. In part, it was due to her support of [[Juan Perón]] and the backlash against his supporters after his [[Revolución Libertadora|ouster in 1955]]. Tania did not return to Argentina until 1959, when she returned to help inaugurate a memorial home for the tango, which became known as "Cambalache", located on Liberty Street near its intersection with Córdoba.<ref name="Nacion obit" /> She wrote her memoirs in 1973 with Jorge Miguel Couselo,<ref name="Pagina 12 obit" /> but tango had gone out of style in the 1960s and would not make a comeback until the 1980s. When worldwide recognition of the genre re-emerged, Tania's recordings from the 1930s and 1940s were at the forefront again.<ref name="Independent, obit" /> From 1983 to 1988 she performed at the Teatro de la Ribera, simultaneously performing in "Botica de Tango" on Channel 11.<ref name="Pagina 12 obit" />
In 1989, she was declared an Illustrious Citizen of the City of Buenos Aires by the city council.<ref name="La Nacion, tribute" /> In 1993, she received from King [[Juan Carlos I of Spain]]<ref name="Clarín obit"/> the [[Order of Isabella the Catholic]] and then in 1998, Tania was declared an Honored Personality of the Culture of Argentina by the Ministry of Culture.<ref name="La Nacion, tribute" /> She died on 17 February 1999 in the apartment she had shared with Discépolo and was buried in [[La Chacarita cemetery|La Chacarita Cemetery]] in Buenos Aires, Argentina.<ref name="Pagina 12 obit" />
